She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

I want to study social work. I will work with Division of Family and Children Services. I help children who are abused or neglected. I also help families with problems.

I will give good values to social work. These are service, respect, and helping others. These values are important to me.

I wanted to help others, but I did not know what job to do. In high school and college, I saw people who had problems. Some people did not face their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. I saw these things and I wanted to help.

I studied psychology in college. I did not know what job to do after college. I took a break. One day, I met a boy who was abused. I went to his house to help. The police asked me to talk to his parents. They said the boy was “manipulative.” The parents did not want to change. I decided to study social work after this.

Social justice is important for social work. People say the individual is important. But many people are the same. I do not like to be the same as others. I fought against bad things in high school and college. I will fight for social justice.

This paper talks about insomnia using two models: Biological and Sociocultural. The Biological model looks at genes and health. The Sociocultural model looks at environment, race, ethnicity, and money. The paper reviews insomnia and explains each model. It also talks about the strengths and weaknesses of each study.

Insomnia is a hard time sleeping. It can be a main problem, or a problem caused by another mental disorder. Other sleep problems can be caused by health or medicines. Main sleep problems are called Dyssomnias. They include Primary Insomnia and Primary Hypersomnia. Other sleep problems are called Parasomnias. They include Nightmare Disorder and Sleepwalking Disorder. This review focuses on insomnia and some primary sleep disorders.

The Biological model of sleep disorders looks at genes and how sleep is controlled. Neurons in the brain control sleep and awake. This study used mice to find out how sleep is controlled. It found that a chemical in the brain helps us sleep. If this chemical doesn't work right, people can't sleep well. This shows that sleep problems can be caused by genes. This can affect school, work, and daily life.

This paper talks about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It defines the disorder and explains how it is diagnosed. Finally, it gives ways teachers can help students with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD is a problem with how the brain processes sounds. People with CAPD can hear normally but have trouble understanding what they hear. They may not hear sounds in space, or have trouble hearing when there is noise. They may also struggle to understand patterns in sounds or changes in speech.

The earliest mention of CAPD was in the 1950s. Researchers called it "auditory imperception". They started testing children with this problem in 1954. In 1961, a scientist named Kimura made a model to explain how it affects the brain. A conference in 1977 started more research on CAPD.

To diagnose CAPD, doctors use tests and watch how well the person listens. There is no one test that works best. Many tests use sounds and ask the person to pick out certain sounds from many. Other tests record sounds in the ear and measure how the person reacts.

Teachers can help students with CAPD in many ways. They can repeat important information. They can use visual aids and reduce background noise. They can also explain things in different ways to help the student understand.

In the play Twelfth Night, disguise can help with long deceptions. But, it can also cause a person to lose themselves. Ending a deception can be hard. People may feel alone. They must decide between staying true to themselves or keeping friends. Some people do not like being tricked. They feel angry. The topic of hiding one's gender is difficult. Why does someone do this? In Viola's case, it is to stay safe. She feels she needs to seem like a man to protect herself. Her plan works, but she loses friends. She also makes Olivia fall in love with her. Olivia thinks Viola is a man named Cesario. Viola also has feelings for Orsino. But, Viola is really a woman. This can be seen as a way to show hidden feelings. In the end, Olivia and Orsino seem to care more about Viola as a sister. They stop looking at her as a possible lover.

German colonial rule was known for its harshness. The murder of Ovaherero and Nama people is a famous example. No one can explain the whole German colonial empire with just this description. The empire had many different policies and ways of ruling. Education in colonies was also very different. In East Africa (Tanganyika), the British found many educated Africans when they took over. In Kamerun and other colonies, German education was also praised. In South West Africa (now Namibia), the situation was very different. Unlike East Africa, where the government taught natives, in South West Africa, missions mostly taught natives. The government only helped a little. The government did more to educate Europeans. These policies lasted a long time even after Germany left. Most people in South West Africa were not educated. Different social, political, and economic factors made South West Africa different. This paper will talk more about these factors and new research on settler and colonial attitudes towards natives.
There is much information about German colonial education. Most sources are in German and were written in the early 1900s. These works describe the education systems in colonies. Later English works compare the education in different German colonies. They also look at specific parts of education. Cohen's study about education in South West Africa and East Africa is the most important for this topic. Cohen says the large settler population in South West Africa explains many differences.
South West Africa had a mild climate, but much of it is desert. The white population was not very big. By 1913, there were nearly 15,000 whites in South West Africa. East Africa had the next biggest settler population, with 5,336 whites.

Popular music has many types. Over 100 years, it has grown and changed. Rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk are some of the main types. Each has many smaller types under them. Heavy metal is one of the most different types. It came from rock and has many small types and even smaller sub-types today. Today, it is hard to say what heavy metal is because it has many kinds and people use many ideas from other types of music.

Metal is a special type of music. It is loud and has strong feelings. It is not like other popular music. It is also influenced by drugs. In the past, people used drugs to make crazy music. Now, many people listen to metal because it has dark and strong feelings. It is different from other music because it has more bass, volume, and loudness. It also has very good music skills. People in metal bands can play their instruments very well.

This text is about Henri Rousseau. He painted dreams. He started painting many years after famous artists. He wanted to be accepted by others. He had a hard choice. He could copy other styles or be different. He did not get formal training. He worked for the government. He lost his family. He painted to feel better. He wanted to be like other artists. He had to wait. Matisse was famous. But Rousseau was different. He liked simple pictures. He wanted to be in the Artiste Français.

Many great thinkers say that ethics and beauty are connected. I think there is a reason for this. John Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty. That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn about life through education and experience. But we also understand ethics and beauty without being taught. Both ethics and beauty try to explain, not tell people what to do. We study them to explain why something is beautiful or moral, not to make rules. Art and moral criticism never fully explain what is good or beautiful. Talking about the Mona Lisa, for example, does not explain why it is good art. People often say, "There's just something about it." This "something" is hard to explain. It is like what Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." We can never fully explain art or morality. Ethics and art are connected because we feel them deeply. They are like what Immanuel Kant called "noumenal." We experience them, but can't explain them fully. This connection is stronger in literature. It is like what McKean said, "Literature's unique quality is its moral quality." It is like life, full of values. Literature is important because of these values.

Germany is a strong country today. It has a blend of culture from the mountains in München to the Baltic Sea in Kiel. This culture can be felt from Köln, through the center of Germany, to the Saxon city of Dresden. Many people believe Germany comes from several tribes.

Germania is the ancient land of the Germans. Some say the name comes from a tribe called Tungrians. Others think it means "spear" in old German. Some also think it means "shout" in old Irish. The Romans called the people "Germani" to show the difference between them and the Gauls.

In 98 AD, Tacitus wrote about the Germans. He said they lived far from Rome. They did not mix with other people. They lived on the borders of the Roman Empire. They traded goods with the Romans. Some Romans used Germanic soldiers.

I looked down, my mind empty. I saw the toilet, not understanding it. I had no thoughts, just feelings. I saw the toilet, and I felt confused.

An artist friend told me to use a book. It's called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I bought it. I wanted to draw since I was six. The book teaches about drawing. It tells how the brain sees lines.

The book says to make a square around the thing you want to study. This makes it easy to understand. I looked at the toilet. It was hard to understand. It was like a bowl of fruit, but worse.

My fingers touched the handle. I tried to move it. I was nervous. I tried again. The toilet did not move. It was stuck.

I grabbed a mop. I put it on the toilet. I waited. I thought. Then I pulled the toilet paper. It was like a turd in the toilet. I was disgusting.

I flushed the toilet. I cleaned it. I felt happy. I did a good job.

Teenagers often die in car accidents. Several reasons cause many young American drivers to have bad accident statistics. The National Institutes of Health says the teen brain is not ready for driving danger. Also, young people have less driving experience. This lack of experience causes more fatal accidents, more vehicle rollover, more speeding, and more driving off the road. Teens fare worse when they drive with friends. A study shows that the number of passengers affects the number of accidents.

Many states try to make teen driving safer by making rules. Provisional licenses limit when teens can drive and stop other minors from being passengers. But these rules are only small fixes. Young drivers do not handle risks and responsibilities well. Some experts say 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today says psychologist Marvin Zuckerman's research shows that teens under 19-20 like to take risks for fun. So, it is important to delay driving until this desire calms down. If we continue to give driver's licenses to young teens, accidents and deaths will increase. By 2010, many new teen drivers will be on the road.

Legislation can help. Schools can teach driving safety. No one under 18 should drive. Permits for provisional licenses can be given before a full license. A set number of driver's training hours should still be required. The number of hours could be like the current hours in many states, such as California. Many states have the same accident problems, so national laws would help protect teens.

This idea is not new.

I looked at the Library of Congress's early Edison films. I saw fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing for illusions. My study focused on describing the tricks in most films and looking at special films from later years. Most trick films from the turn of the century are set-bound and use no camera movement. They use long and medium shots and follow the rule of one shot equals one film. Some films from the start of the twentieth century break these rules with multiple shots.
One common thing in trick films is the filming in an indoor set with a frontal stage. The camera stays in the same spot. This was common in early films and came from theatre and vaudeville. Figures in trick films usually move side-to-side, not towards or away from the camera. In Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors move right and left, but the camera does not follow them.
Trick films use long and medium shots, never close-ups. This is like theatre and vaudeville, where the audience sees the whole performance. Actors do not move towards the camera, so close-ups do not happen.
Most trick films follow the rule of one shot equals one film. This makes trick films short, usually under a minute. They often show simple tricks, not stories. However, one "shot" can be several films joined together to make an illusion. In The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), the film starts with Mary's "head" appearing, but it is actually made from many joined shots.

John Taylor from Caroline was a early and strong supporter of the Republican party. He was a farmer, and his brief time in politics made him known for his strong beliefs in personal freedom and government. His love for farming made him believe that the best government supports farmers.

John Taylor thought the United States had a chance to create a great system because there were no old traditions to stop it. He believed strongly in human rights and that they all depend on each other. He thought the government should not take these rights.

Taylor believed that a good government should deal with people's good and bad sides. He thought that a government with good rules would be fair, even if leaders were not. He thought self-interest was not always bad, but it could be if it caused harm to others. A good government must watch for bad rules.

Taylor wanted a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He thought the federal government should have only the powers listed in the Constitution. He knew a big government could be bad. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true rules of the United States.

In Figure 17, commuter log submissions dropped sharply in the third month. This was disappointing. We do not know why. Winter might have caused fewer people to commute by bicycle or walking. December is also the end of the fall semester. Students and faculty are busy finishing work and processing grades. Commuter logs might have been forgotten. Also, December is the start of the busy holiday season. Many do not need to go to campus. Classes resume in late January. This might explain the low number of logs in February. The project might have had an initial burst of energy. Then, energy might naturally decrease. To fix this, we made the Carpool Challenge Week in March. This increased log submissions. So, we faced two challenges: maintaining project momentum and changing people's habits. People like driving cars. We gave out many prizes. These included gift certificates for local stores and larger chain stores. We also considered giving away a bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have helped. The value of the prizes did not change. If we had announced larger prizes in December and January, more people might have participated.

An ETF is a security designed to track an index, commodity, or group of assets. It trades like a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer diversification like index funds. They also allow short selling, margin buying, and buying one share. ETFs usually have lower fees than mutual funds. However, you pay a commission for trades. There are many ETFs to choose from. This report will compare ETF IHF with its top 10 holdings to see if owning one ETF is better than buying the top 10 stocks directly.

We will look at the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. Here are the holdings and their percentages:

To see how well the top 10 stocks represent the ETF, we will calculate their contribution to Beta and return. The chart below shows these calculations:

The top 10 holdings give a 6.11% higher return than the ETF. The Beta is 0.12 lower. This suggests a better return and lower risk. However, the difference may not be statistically significant. To check, we will compare the standard deviation of each top 10 stock and the ETF IHF.

Dream-Land is a famous poem by Edgar Allan Poe. In this poem, Poe uses the word Thule in lines 6 and 56. This word comes from Virgil. Virgil used it to describe a place far away, beyond the known world. However, another writer also used this word. Poe was interested in German writers, especially Goethe. Karl J. Arndt said that Poe's poem looks like Goethe's work, so Poe might have copied it. The Oxford Companion says that Goethe wrote a famous drama called Faust. In the second part of Faust, there is a short poem called The King of Thule. This poem tells about a king whose wife dies, and he becomes very sad. He drinks too much and wants to die. Poe might have used Thule in his poem because he was thinking of this story. Poe used Thule twice in his writings. In The Pit and the Pendulum, he used the phrase "ultma Thule." He also used it twice in Dream-Land, at the beginning and end of the poem. These two poems might be connected. In Dream-Land, the speaker describes a dark, lonely place called Thule. This is like the story of The King of Thule. Poe might have been thinking about this poem when he wrote Dream-Land. Goethe was very famous, and Poe might have known about him because he admired another writer, Tennyson. Poe might have read Goethe's work because many people were reproducing it after the original publication.

Under California law, a store customer who slipped and fell on applesauce in a grocery store might get extra money (punitive damages) if the store manager acted badly (with malice). This means the manager knew the customer could get hurt, but did nothing to stop it.

A judge is not likely to throw out Jennifer Palmer's claim. To win, she must show the manager did something very wrong, like acting with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm. She can say:
- The manager knew about other slip-and-fall incidents.
- Despite knowing this, he did not clean the spill for 30 minutes.
- His actions were bad (despicable).

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, an employee told the manager about an applesauce spill. The manager was on dinner break and did not clean it. Another employee also told him at 5:15 PM, but he still did nothing. At 5:30 PM, Jennifer Palmer fell and got hurt. Before her accident, five other slip-and-fall incidents had happened in 2009.

California law lets customers get punitive damages if a store owner acts with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Malice means the owner wanted to cause harm, or did something very wrong without caring about the harm. If the manager was aware of the danger and did nothing, it can be considered malicious.

Palmer is suing for both compensatory and punitive damages. We will consider if a motion to dismiss the punitive damage claim makes sense.

Four years ago, I took a religion class about Islam at CBC. In class, we talked about if Islam is a bad religion. I think this question is still important today. After 9/11, the way people see Islam in America changed. In 2001, no one expected a Muslim president like Obama. The Prophet Muhammad's story interests me. What I know about him seems different from the story. I thought Muhammad forced people to become Muslim. But the story says he was humble and people came to him. The story also has things like Jesus's miracles. This makes me think the writers want us to believe Muhammad was like Jesus. The story wants us to believe people joined Islam on their own. But many stories are from other people. I don't like that because it makes the stories less true. I also don't like that the story makes Muhammad seem like a good man. But history says he was not so good. I think Muslims today should know the truth about Muhammad.

Jesus taught ideas and beliefs that became different in Christianity after his life. Over time, Christianity changed and moved away from its start. Today, people are more aware and open to new thinking. Some people may resist these ideas. But in the future, Christians will want to understand Jesus' real teachings. They will remove layers of new beliefs. This will happen over many years. When this happens, there may be more uniform beliefs in Christianity. History shows that things can change greatly. For example, Christians were once not liked by the Romans, but later the Romans became Christian. This change has happened in the U.S. and Europe too. We may see this change in Christianity too. It will be important to understand Jesus' words as metaphors, not just as literal meanings. In the past, there was only Judaism, the start of Christianity. God, a revealed religion, and the Hebrew Bible were important. People in Judaism had different beliefs. There were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a large group of common people.

The Jungle shows people are greedy and selfish. They only think about themselves. They do not care about others. The owners and managers of big factories want to make their companies big. They do not care about people or animals that get hurt. They do not care about pollution from factories. They do not care about employees. They make workers work long hours. They do not care about workers' safety. They have no laws to help workers. Workers are like slaves. They have no way to escape.

Sinclair shows factory owners do not care about people or animals. He shows pollution from factories. He shows bad working conditions. Workers are badly treated. They have no help. They live in a bad system. They are like slaves.

Many writers use different ways to make readers feel or think about important things. Some ways are better than others. Fitzgerald uses many of these ways in his book called The Great Gatsby.

Sometimes, he pairs words that don't usually go together to make readers feel a certain way about a subject. Other times, he gives a meaning to a symbol and then uses it again and again.

Fitzgerald uses this method with many colors. He uses gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald makes colors have special meaning. He uses white/gray to mean the same thing and red/pink to mean something different.

He shows white/gray to be the same in the beginning of the book. People wear white and gray a lot. For example, Daisy and Jordan wear white, and Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party. The only time people don't wear white is when Nick is at Gatsby's party. Fitzgerald also uses white/gray to describe common things. He says that people are "white" or "gray". He says that the Italian child is "gray" and the dog-seller is "a gray old man".

After Fitzgerald makes these meanings, he uses white/gray to show that something is not important or uniform. He first uses this with Daisy. When Daisy is not used in the story for a long time, Fitzgerald says she is "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster". This makes readers think she is just a part of Gatsby's dream, not a real person. He also uses this method with Daisy's fur collar, which is "a gray haze", and her dress, which is "white".

San Diego County has a mild, sunny climate. This makes it good for growing many things. These include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers.

There is a market for organic food in San Diego. Many people want organic eggs and milk. Organic farms often have tours. They also allow people to hike and watch birds.

This kind of farming is good for the land and wildlife. It has more biodiversity. But it also has high costs. It needs more labor and management. It has more losses than conventional farming. Small farms lack the efficiency of large ones.

The land chosen for this example is in Potrero, unincorporated San Diego County. It is 160 acres. It has chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland. It is next to the Cleveland National Forest.

This area has many plants and animals. Some are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the California gnatcatcher. Others are declining. This area was used by Native Americans and later by cattle ranchers.

I looked at a real estate website for a farm. I found programs to help small farmers. I used an organic farm in the same area as a model.

Culture is important in talks. Culture is not one thing. It is not the same in all places. Saying "all Russians are tough" or "all Japanese are friendly" is not true. It is better to understand how a culture affects talks. When you meet a new culture, you compare it to your own. To understand a new culture, you can learn its history or understand its beliefs. Do not judge or try to change a culture. Accept it and work within it, especially if you are not strong in talks. If you are in a new place, show respect for traditions and beliefs. This can help in talks.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies also have their own culture. This can be seen in how employees dress, how they talk, and how they hire people. Some companies value long hours, others value work-life balance. Even in the same country, companies can be different. Values are important. If a culture values harmony, you must not make others look bad. If a culture values tough deals, you must not settle easily. Understand these things before talks. But also, learn about your opponent personally to make talks work.

"The fool said, 'God does not exist.' This idea is found in Psalm 14. It starts St. Anselm's argument about God. He believes that because God is in our minds, we know he exists. He says, 'The proof for God is in our own minds.' This is different from St. Thomas Aquinas who thinks we can prove God exists using reason and evidence. He gives five reasons: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. He says God's existence is logical and can be understood without faith. Both are correct but neither is enough to prove God's existence.

Buddha was born long ago, maybe in the fifth or sixth century BCE. He became a wise teacher, and this led to Buddhism. Theravada Buddhism is the main type, and it has been around for about 2500 years. It looks different today than when Buddha was alive. For example, in Sri Lanka, there is a water-cutting ceremony. Monks and laypeople take part in this ceremony. It has important meaning, even if Buddha did not teach about it. Many things have changed in Theravada Buddhism over time. This is because of both good and bad forces, inside and outside the Buddhist community.

We will use special words in this discussion. Internal forces come from Buddhists, no matter if they are monks or not. External forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces harm or try to harm the Buddhist community. Benign forces do not want to harm or help the community, but they might do so by accident.

First, let's look at the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find comfort in the triple gem: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is the teachings, written in three books: Sutta Pitaka, Vinaya Pitaka, and Abhidhamma Pitaka. These books talk about Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). By understanding these, one can escape Sansara (cycle of death and rebirth) and end lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. There are five rules for laypeople and many more for monks. The most important teaching is the Four Noble Truths: life has suffering, attachment causes suffering, and suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico had a big disagreement for a long time. This disagreement lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The biggest problem was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848. The United States won and got more land. Other problems happened too, but they stopped before World War I.

Many nations have problems with their neighbors. Nations that share a border often have different ideas about what they want. The United States and Mexico are not different. They have had many problems, just like Mexico and Cuba. David M. Pletcher says, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can you find long-lasting American problems" (p. 41).

Religion made the United States and Mexico have big disagreements. Sally Frahm says, "Americans were against fascism and communism in the 20th century, but they were against Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries" (p.86). The fight between the United States and Mexico was not just about power, but also about religion. This fight came from the bad feelings between English and Spanish. This made it hard for the United States and Mexico to be good friends.

Diehl and Goerts list 17 problems between Mexico and the United States in 57 years. Most problems were about the border. Mexican bandits and outlaws caused many problems. Both countries had to use their military to stop these problems.

The disagreement between the United States and Mexico became less bad when Mexico started to depend on the United States a lot. It ended when American goals changed from getting more land to helping Mexico with money.

Fifteen years ago, I got sick suddenly. I did not know I had it. I was a nurse. I chose this job because it was safe and secure. I heard, "You can always find work. People will always get sick."

I wanted to be a scientist or a journalist. But I chose nursing.

At 46, I got sick again. I could not work. I have money problems. I live on Social Security Disability. I struggle every day. Nothing is certain.

My family and friends helped me. Without them, I could not have survived.

Life has emergencies. No one can prepare for everything alone.

In the US, we should trust each other. We should help each other. We should ask for help.

Conservatives say rugged individualism built the country. But our forefathers needed compassion and sharing.

So, prepare. I have a disaster kit. I have food and supplies. But also, know your neighbors.

Organisms change over time because of evolution. What makes these changes happen? Are there rules that control evolution? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that even today, scientists don't understand the simplest shapes of living things using math. But now, math is used to study how mollusks grow and change. Our study uses math and experiments to find out how mollusks grow and change. We use x-ray pictures of Prunum shells to find numbers that help us make models of shell shapes. We use CerioShell software to make these models. The models help us understand how Prunum shells can change. We also look at real and experimental studies to understand bigger changes in this group. A shell is like a tube that turns around in 360 degrees. Each turn is called a whorl. The middle part of the shell is called the columella. The fastest and slowest parts of the shell are the aperture and the base. Shells can be seen from different angles. We count whorls by starting from the top and counting. We can trace the path of the aperture. This path can be shown with math. Once we have a math formula, we can change things and see how the shell grows.

The rate of neonatal and infant death in Indonesia has not changed much in the last ten years. While the country is close to meeting water and sanitation targets, child and maternal health has not improved as much as needed to meet 2015 goals.

Many reasons cause this. We need to improve the health system, not just specific programs.

Indonesia has more births with skilled workers, but many are traditional workers who cannot help with complicated pregnancies. This explains many maternal deaths.

There are also fewer cases of young children with diarrhea treated by health workers. Postnatal care is a problem too.

Cesarean rates are low and worse in rural areas. This shows that rural people do not get good health care. The rich have better access than the poor.

Next, we must decide how to improve these health indicators. We can focus on specific programs or improve the whole health system.

Programs are good because they focus on one area. But they may not help other areas and can cause duplication of services.

Victorian novels usually focus on details and the rich people of that time. Two books, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," are different. These books use mystery and strange events to make characters stronger. They show the characters' thoughts and feelings.

In "Oliver Twist," strange things happen in dreams or dream-like states. These dreams show Oliver's inner feelings and his awareness of what is happening around him. When Oliver is shot, he relives the event in a dream. He has no control over what happens. His health is bad, and he feels fear and pain. The shooting makes it clear that Oliver cannot control his life. He also feels defeated, like he cannot help himself.

The passage about the long night shows how time passes quickly and quietly. It is both long and short at the same time.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program helping young students. I tried to help them in subjects they struggled with, especially in reading. One student was named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade and had trouble reading. I noticed his reading problems were weird. He could say some letters correctly, but others not at all. Adrian spoke perfect English, but his mother only spoke Spanish. We talked in Spanish, but my Spanish was bad. Adrian could read, but he didn't know the English alphabet well. Tutoring helped him, but I hope he's doing better now.

This story helps show the language barrier in schools, especially in California. Even if a child speaks perfect English, reading can be hard. Many children have language problems. No one solution helps all children. We need to combine many things.

The dual language system is good. It helps children who speak Spanish and other children too. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs do better academically." Many people are afraid this is a waste of resources. They think most children won't benefit. But this is not true. If we use these programs in all classes, all children will benefit. How can we do this? We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. We can have special helpers who speak two languages.

Many people are told about something bigger than themselves when they are young. Some go to church, others explore inside themselves. Some accept the beliefs their parents have. But others reject them. Everyone has a unique way to understand spirituality. They search for a guide to bring light in the dark.

“Cardinal,” my father said. He liked this bird. We sat on the porch, it was raining. We smoked cigarettes. He looked at the rain, thinking. He was thin, his hair was less. He did not look at me. I felt alone, scared. I hugged him. I sat close. I looked at the rain with him.

My father died in December. The medicine and treatment did not help him. I did not watch him die. I wanted to remember him by how he lived. I did not tell anyone. I lay in bed for three days. I waited for news. No one called me.

The word "Gothic Novel" is like "old-new." This is what Ian Watt said in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. Many people said good and bad things about Gothic stories. Some said they had no real depth. Others said they were very exciting. The first Gothic story, The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, mixed old and new ideas to make a new type of story. Walpole used old theater ideas and new nature mimicry in his "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). Gothic stories use old ideas from medieval theater, architecture, and traditions. The word "gothic" was used for many things at that time. People thought it was old-fashioned. The mix of old theatrical Gothic and new novel format made Gothic last a long time. It became old and new to people far from the original time.

One important idea in Gothic stories is Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, training a knight, is shown in the first Gothic story, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is important because it represents brave, honorable knights. Writers saw this ideal in the past, but not in the present. They used chivalric ideas to make the past look good and romantic. This hinted at the future of Gothic becoming Romantic. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a time of political trouble. He was sad about the future. He may have thought people in the past were better than people in his time. This is shown in the character Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, he seems to have many chivalric traits. He is a prince, has suffered, and is supposed to be killed by infidels. The description of him includes many chivalric images. He is a brave and courteous knight, but this is exaggerated to show the soon-to-be Gothic idea of excess (66).

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from the customer order through raw materials, production, and distribution to the customer.

Keith Oliver, a consultant, invented the term in 1982. He described how to plan, do, and control the supply chain to quickly and efficiently meet customer needs.

There are six important parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the base for the whole process. Managers need to know what customers want. They look at the market to understand this.

After knowing customer demand, managers decide what products to make and how many. They also decide where to make them and which plant is best.

After knowing production location, managers focus on scheduling work and equipment maintenance.

Each detail in production is important. If not planned well, it can cost a company time and money.

For example, in my past jobs at Wal-Mart and Target, we had clear processes for everything. This helped us work smoothly without confusion.

The second key part is supply. Supply is about making strategic decisions to decide what the facility should do and where to outsource work. A company might have many divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager decides which division is best for each part of the product.

A manager might also outsource work to other companies to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide good quality and flexibility while reducing costs or keeping costs low.

Hitler alive in Burma. This is bad. Ellen Page holds sign with message about it. Burma is a country in Asia. A bad group runs the country. They take power by force. They keep people quiet. In 2007, people protest against them. Monks lead the protests. Many people join. At first, the group lets the monks protest. But then, they fight back. They hurt people. Many die. The world knows about this. But not all. This is not new. Many bad things happen in our world. This happens often. Many people die. All over the world.

Duke Ellington made jazz music for a long time and was very good at it. He used his band like a big family. He wrote music that showed each player's skills. He let solo players make music freely. He also wrote music that fit the band together. This made his music sound good and new.

The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington used voice like an instrument. Creole Love Call is an example. The voice starts smooth and then gets rougher. The band plays different sounds too. The music has six parts. Each part has a different sound and a different player's voice. Some parts have many instruments. Some parts have just one instrument. The music ends with a trombone playing a funny sound.

In later music, Ellington uses voices and instruments together. In Hot and Bothered, a trumpet and a voice play together. In It Don’t Mean a Thing, a trombone plays the main tune. Ellington made these songs with tight music and different sounds. This is what makes his music special.

She always felt she needed something. This desire stayed with her, even when she was 17. She wanted someone, not a thing. No boy interested her. She wondered why. She lived, asking herself.

At home, she had good, calm parents. They argued little, even with her. She was independent. Today, she heard a scream. Her mother was in pain. She helped her to the car and drove to the hospital. Doctors looked at her mother. She fell from a stool.

This study shows that eating a Mediterranean diet (Med diet) can lower the risk of heart disease (CHD) and stroke. The study used a modified Med diet, called the alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet. It has more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes. It also has more monounsaturated fats and less saturated fats. It allows some alcohol.

Past studies said eating a Med diet can lower the risk of death from heart disease and other heart problems. But they did not look at stroke.

This study followed 74,886 nurses from 1984 to 2004. They had no heart disease or diabetes. The nurses filled out food frequency questionnaires (FFQs) six times. The study used aMed diet scores from these questionnaires. More than 95% of nurses stuck with the study for 20 years. The study checked for heart disease and stroke cases from medical records, hospital records, or death certificates. It also looked at other factors like weight, smoking, aspirin use, and physical activity.

The study used a special math method to make sure the results were not just a mistake. It found that women who ate more like the Mediterranean diet had less risk of heart disease and stroke. During 20 years, 2391 women had heart disease and 1763 had strokes. Women who ate the most like the Mediterranean diet had less risk than those who ate the least (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the USA had a big financial problem. Many people lost jobs. The housing market fell apart. Big companies in America were in big trouble. This is still a problem today. We should ask: How did this happen, and how can we stop it? The financial crisis started because some important decisions were made. Banks and companies gave loans to people who couldn't pay back. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac helped make these bad loans into new things called CDOs and CDS. When people couldn't pay, the banks didn't have enough money to fix the problem. They passed it on to other investors and the whole economy. The crisis started in 1999 under President Clinton. He wanted to stay in office, so he made rules easier to get loans. This was not good. A reporter, Steven Holmes, warned about it. He said Fannie Mae might have big problems if there was a recession. Many things made the crisis worse. New types of mortgages made it harder for people to pay. The housing market was like a big bubble. It burst and made many banks and companies very poor. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were taken over by the government.

Exposition is part of your story where you show how things happened. It is like telling the audience what is happening. In a story, exposition can be good or bad. Good exposition is like showing the audience what happened. Bad exposition is like telling the audience too much information. The author's job is to show the audience what is happening, not just tell them.

Showing is better than telling. It is like showing the audience what is happening, not just telling them what is happening. For example, in a story, the audience should see the heroine meet her husband and see how they feel about each other. They should see the husband's character and the heroine's character. They should see how they are connected.

If you tell the audience too much information, they might not understand the story. They might get bored or confused. So, you should show them what is happening, not just tell them.

I watched two news stories from Columbus, Ohio. The first story was live on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). A man named Shad Hostettler stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They showed his picture and said he looked dangerous. They talked only about this story for two minutes. The second story was about a shooting in Sharon Woods. A young man named Travis Buyers was shot and was in critical condition. No one was arrested yet. The SWAT team was looking for the shooter. This story was short. I think this might be because the victim was black. Sometimes, the media does not talk about crimes when the victim is black. The next story was about a bullet hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. They thought the bullet was from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a reward for information about the shooter. The next story was about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday. They said the temperatures would be in the mid to low eighties. The last story was about a robbery at a store on Clime Road. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. They talked about this story a long time, and they said he was black many times. The last story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug boss in Texas. He was arrested for selling drugs in Ohio. They talked about his sentence in months, not years. They also said he was Hispanic, but that was not important to the story.

Brothers have a special bond. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other more than other people. They see themselves in their brothers. When things are bad, the bond shows. Good or bad, it has a cost. We must deal with the feelings this bond brings. When we look into our brother’s eyes, we see our true self. Our actions show our true character. In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers show this theme. They go on a journey in a beautiful place. They feel sad and proud at the end. Only one brother lives. The story shows the main character, Doodle, and his feelings. The narrator also shows his feelings. This influences the main character’s actions.

The main character feels proud. He wants to teach his brother many things. He wants a brother to race with and climb with. But his brother, Doodle, is very sick. He has a weak heart. The main character is disappointed. He feels angry. He even thinks about killing Doodle. But Doodle smiles at him. This makes the main character feel better. He loves Doodle. His love is strong.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information processor. As technology changes, the way we describe the brain also changes. Before, we compared the brain to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and now to a computer. Remember, these comparisons can be wrong.
Information starts when our senses take in things from the world. Our senses turn physical things like touch, heat, sound, and light into signals. The brain changes these signals many times using algorithms. This is called bottom-up processing. It uses simple information like color, shape, and where objects are to understand what we see. Top-down processing helps us recognize things faster. It uses decisions made by the brain earlier. For example, when you see a black box on a white background, top-down processing helps you see it as a box and not a hole.
Once the brain understands something, an attention filter decides if it is important. This filter can decide what information to give to our minds. For example, when you look at your shoes, your brain notices many things, but the filter helps you ignore them. But, if you hear your name in a noisy room, your brain picks it out.
The brain needs to store information. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is stored differently based on what it is. For example, words can be stored based on how they look, sound, or mean. Working memory lasts for about 20 seconds. In long-term memory, information is stored in certain proteins.
There are different ways to understand how the brain stores and organizes knowledge. Some ways are based on what people remember, others are based on computer science, and others are based on the brain's physical workings. One model is the semantic network. It says there are nodes for concepts and they are linked based on their connection. For example, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which is linked to “wooden.”

Aldous Huxley in his book Brave New World criticizes the danger of new technologies and the capitalist system. People value group happiness over individual happiness. They are taught from birth to want instant happiness. They are like pawns in a game controlled by the World Controller. Huxley is suspicious of these systems. He uses Marxist ideas to show their problems. People do not understand their true place in the economy. They are controlled by the upper class. Lower classes want to buy and spend. They do not see the manipulation. Upper classes know but do not act. The story shows how people are controlled by capitalism. In Brave New World, people do not have deep relationships. They talk about physical appearance. They are happy with their place in society. They obey. This is like the Marxist idea of the proletariat being happy with their place.

I have been a student at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Many students, including me, find it hard to get around campus. My freshman year, I lived in East Halls, the farthest dorm from the center of campus. Walking to classes, like in the Willard building, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather. In the past, East Halls was far from the rest of the school. Now, new sports fields and buildings, like the new Creamery and health services, have been built there. As campus grows, it becomes harder to move around. What's the best solution? Bicycles are helpful, but they won't work alone. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be friendly for bicycles.

I talked to a friend who started riding his bike again after a long break. He said, "Bikes are great. They are the best way to get around." Bicycling is good for your body and fast. You can travel far with just oatmeal and a bit of effort. I now live off campus, far from the center. This year, I bought a bike. Class in Thomas building, 25 minutes walk from my house, takes only 5 minutes by bike. Pollock Road is the fastest way to get there by bike, but it's not always easy. Walking is an option, but I am too busy. Without my bike, walking would be my only choice. Walking to Thomas every day would take 30-40 minutes. That's more than two and a half hours a week. Adding time for other classes and appointments, it's too much time.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified.
