The rate of neonatal and infant death in Indonesia has not changed much in the last ten years. While the country is close to meeting water and sanitation targets, child and maternal health has not improved as much as needed to meet 2015 goals.

Many reasons cause this. We need to improve the health system, not just specific programs.

Indonesia has more births with skilled workers, but many are traditional workers who cannot help with complicated pregnancies. This explains many maternal deaths.

There are also fewer cases of young children with diarrhea treated by health workers. Postnatal care is a problem too.

Cesarean rates are low and worse in rural areas. This shows that rural people do not get good health care. The rich have better access than the poor.

Next, we must decide how to improve these health indicators. We can focus on specific programs or improve the whole health system.

Programs are good because they focus on one area. But they may not help other areas and can cause duplication of services.

Victorian novels usually focus on details and the rich people of that time. Two books, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," are different. These books use mystery and strange events to make characters stronger. They show the characters' thoughts and feelings.

In "Oliver Twist," strange things happen in dreams or dream-like states. These dreams show Oliver's inner feelings and his awareness of what is happening around him. When Oliver is shot, he relives the event in a dream. He has no control over what happens. His health is bad, and he feels fear and pain. The shooting makes it clear that Oliver cannot control his life. He also feels defeated, like he cannot help himself.

The passage about the long night shows how time passes quickly and quietly. It is both long and short at the same time.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program helping young students. I tried to help them in subjects they struggled with, especially in reading. One student was named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade and had trouble reading. I noticed his reading problems were weird. He could say some letters correctly, but others not at all. Adrian spoke perfect English, but his mother only spoke Spanish. We talked in Spanish, but my Spanish was bad. Adrian could read, but he didn't know the English alphabet well. Tutoring helped him, but I hope he's doing better now.

This story helps show the language barrier in schools, especially in California. Even if a child speaks perfect English, reading can be hard. Many children have language problems. No one solution helps all children. We need to combine many things.

The dual language system is good. It helps children who speak Spanish and other children too. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs do better academically." Many people are afraid this is a waste of resources. They think most children won't benefit. But this is not true. If we use these programs in all classes, all children will benefit. How can we do this? We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. We can have special helpers who speak two languages.

Many people are told about something bigger than themselves when they are young. Some go to church, others explore inside themselves. Some accept the beliefs their parents have. But others reject them. Everyone has a unique way to understand spirituality. They search for a guide to bring light in the dark.

“Cardinal,” my father said. He liked this bird. We sat on the porch, it was raining. We smoked cigarettes. He looked at the rain, thinking. He was thin, his hair was less. He did not look at me. I felt alone, scared. I hugged him. I sat close. I looked at the rain with him.

My father died in December. The medicine and treatment did not help him. I did not watch him die. I wanted to remember him by how he lived. I did not tell anyone. I lay in bed for three days. I waited for news. No one called me.

The word "Gothic Novel" is like "old-new." This is what Ian Watt said in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. Many people said good and bad things about Gothic stories. Some said they had no real depth. Others said they were very exciting. The first Gothic story, The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, mixed old and new ideas to make a new type of story. Walpole used old theater ideas and new nature mimicry in his "Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). Gothic stories use old ideas from medieval theater, architecture, and traditions. The word "gothic" was used for many things at that time. People thought it was old-fashioned. The mix of old theatrical Gothic and new novel format made Gothic last a long time. It became old and new to people far from the original time.

One important idea in Gothic stories is Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, training a knight, is shown in the first Gothic story, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is important because it represents brave, honorable knights. Writers saw this ideal in the past, but not in the present. They used chivalric ideas to make the past look good and romantic. This hinted at the future of Gothic becoming Romantic. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto during a time of political trouble. He was sad about the future. He may have thought people in the past were better than people in his time. This is shown in the character Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, he seems to have many chivalric traits. He is a prince, has suffered, and is supposed to be killed by infidels. The description of him includes many chivalric images. He is a brave and courteous knight, but this is exaggerated to show the soon-to-be Gothic idea of excess (66).

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from the customer order through raw materials, production, and distribution to the customer.

Keith Oliver, a consultant, invented the term in 1982. He described how to plan, do, and control the supply chain to quickly and efficiently meet customer needs.

There are six important parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the base for the whole process. Managers need to know what customers want. They look at the market to understand this.

After knowing customer demand, managers decide what products to make and how many. They also decide where to make them and which plant is best.

After knowing production location, managers focus on scheduling work and equipment maintenance.

Each detail in production is important. If not planned well, it can cost a company time and money.

For example, in my past jobs at Wal-Mart and Target, we had clear processes for everything. This helped us work smoothly without confusion.

The second key part is supply. Supply is about making strategic decisions to decide what the facility should do and where to outsource work. A company might have many divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager decides which division is best for each part of the product.

A manager might also outsource work to other companies to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide good quality and flexibility while reducing costs or keeping costs low.

Hitler alive in Burma. This is bad. Ellen Page holds sign with message about it. Burma is a country in Asia. A bad group runs the country. They take power by force. They keep people quiet. In 2007, people protest against them. Monks lead the protests. Many people join. At first, the group lets the monks protest. But then, they fight back. They hurt people. Many die. The world knows about this. But not all. This is not new. Many bad things happen in our world. This happens often. Many people die. All over the world.

Duke Ellington made jazz music for a long time and was very good at it. He used his band like a big family. He wrote music that showed each player's skills. He let solo players make music freely. He also wrote music that fit the band together. This made his music sound good and new.

The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington used voice like an instrument. Creole Love Call is an example. The voice starts smooth and then gets rougher. The band plays different sounds too. The music has six parts. Each part has a different sound and a different player's voice. Some parts have many instruments. Some parts have just one instrument. The music ends with a trombone playing a funny sound.

In later music, Ellington uses voices and instruments together. In Hot and Bothered, a trumpet and a voice play together. In It Don’t Mean a Thing, a trombone plays the main tune. Ellington made these songs with tight music and different sounds. This is what makes his music special.

She always felt she needed something. This desire stayed with her, even when she was 17. She wanted someone, not a thing. No boy interested her. She wondered why. She lived, asking herself.

At home, she had good, calm parents. They argued little, even with her. She was independent. Today, she heard a scream. Her mother was in pain. She helped her to the car and drove to the hospital. Doctors looked at her mother. She fell from a stool.

This study shows that eating a Mediterranean diet (Med diet) can lower the risk of heart disease (CHD) and stroke. The study used a modified Med diet, called the alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet. It has more plant foods, like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes. It also has more monounsaturated fats and less saturated fats. It allows some alcohol.

Past studies said eating a Med diet can lower the risk of death from heart disease and other heart problems. But they did not look at stroke.

This study followed 74,886 nurses from 1984 to 2004. They had no heart disease or diabetes. The nurses filled out food frequency questionnaires (FFQs) six times. The study used aMed diet scores from these questionnaires. More than 95% of nurses stuck with the study for 20 years. The study checked for heart disease and stroke cases from medical records, hospital records, or death certificates. It also looked at other factors like weight, smoking, aspirin use, and physical activity.

The study used a special math method to make sure the results were not just a mistake. It found that women who ate more like the Mediterranean diet had less risk of heart disease and stroke. During 20 years, 2391 women had heart disease and 1763 had strokes. Women who ate the most like the Mediterranean diet had less risk than those who ate the least (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the USA had a big financial problem. Many people lost jobs. The housing market fell apart. Big companies in America were in big trouble. This is still a problem today. We should ask: How did this happen, and how can we stop it? The financial crisis started because some important decisions were made. Banks and companies gave loans to people who couldn't pay back. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac helped make these bad loans into new things called CDOs and CDS. When people couldn't pay, the banks didn't have enough money to fix the problem. They passed it on to other investors and the whole economy. The crisis started in 1999 under President Clinton. He wanted to stay in office, so he made rules easier to get loans. This was not good. A reporter, Steven Holmes, warned about it. He said Fannie Mae might have big problems if there was a recession. Many things made the crisis worse. New types of mortgages made it harder for people to pay. The housing market was like a big bubble. It burst and made many banks and companies very poor. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were taken over by the government.

Exposition is part of your story where you show how things happened. It is like telling the audience what is happening. In a story, exposition can be good or bad. Good exposition is like showing the audience what happened. Bad exposition is like telling the audience too much information. The author's job is to show the audience what is happening, not just tell them.

Showing is better than telling. It is like showing the audience what is happening, not just telling them what is happening. For example, in a story, the audience should see the heroine meet her husband and see how they feel about each other. They should see the husband's character and the heroine's character. They should see how they are connected.

If you tell the audience too much information, they might not understand the story. They might get bored or confused. So, you should show them what is happening, not just tell them.

I watched two news stories from Columbus, Ohio. The first story was live on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). A man named Shad Hostettler stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. They showed his picture and said he looked dangerous. They talked only about this story for two minutes. The second story was about a shooting in Sharon Woods. A young man named Travis Buyers was shot and was in critical condition. No one was arrested yet. The SWAT team was looking for the shooter. This story was short. I think this might be because the victim was black. Sometimes, the media does not talk about crimes when the victim is black. The next story was about a bullet hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. They thought the bullet was from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a reward for information about the shooter. The next story was about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday. They said the temperatures would be in the mid to low eighties. The last story was about a robbery at a store on Clime Road. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. They talked about this story a long time, and they said he was black many times. The last story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug boss in Texas. He was arrested for selling drugs in Ohio. They talked about his sentence in months, not years. They also said he was Hispanic, but that was not important to the story.

Brothers have a special bond. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other more than other people. They see themselves in their brothers. When things are bad, the bond shows. Good or bad, it has a cost. We must deal with the feelings this bond brings. When we look into our brother’s eyes, we see our true self. Our actions show our true character. In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers show this theme. They go on a journey in a beautiful place. They feel sad and proud at the end. Only one brother lives. The story shows the main character, Doodle, and his feelings. The narrator also shows his feelings. This influences the main character’s actions.

The main character feels proud. He wants to teach his brother many things. He wants a brother to race with and climb with. But his brother, Doodle, is very sick. He has a weak heart. The main character is disappointed. He feels angry. He even thinks about killing Doodle. But Doodle smiles at him. This makes the main character feel better. He loves Doodle. His love is strong.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information processor. As technology changes, the way we describe the brain also changes. Before, we compared the brain to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and now to a computer. Remember, these comparisons can be wrong.
Information starts when our senses take in things from the world. Our senses turn physical things like touch, heat, sound, and light into signals. The brain changes these signals many times using algorithms. This is called bottom-up processing. It uses simple information like color, shape, and where objects are to understand what we see. Top-down processing helps us recognize things faster. It uses decisions made by the brain earlier. For example, when you see a black box on a white background, top-down processing helps you see it as a box and not a hole.
Once the brain understands something, an attention filter decides if it is important. This filter can decide what information to give to our minds. For example, when you look at your shoes, your brain notices many things, but the filter helps you ignore them. But, if you hear your name in a noisy room, your brain picks it out.
The brain needs to store information. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is stored differently based on what it is. For example, words can be stored based on how they look, sound, or mean. Working memory lasts for about 20 seconds. In long-term memory, information is stored in certain proteins.
There are different ways to understand how the brain stores and organizes knowledge. Some ways are based on what people remember, others are based on computer science, and others are based on the brain's physical workings. One model is the semantic network. It says there are nodes for concepts and they are linked based on their connection. For example, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which is linked to “wooden.”

Aldous Huxley in his book Brave New World criticizes the danger of new technologies and the capitalist system. People value group happiness over individual happiness. They are taught from birth to want instant happiness. They are like pawns in a game controlled by the World Controller. Huxley is suspicious of these systems. He uses Marxist ideas to show their problems. People do not understand their true place in the economy. They are controlled by the upper class. Lower classes want to buy and spend. They do not see the manipulation. Upper classes know but do not act. The story shows how people are controlled by capitalism. In Brave New World, people do not have deep relationships. They talk about physical appearance. They are happy with their place in society. They obey. This is like the Marxist idea of the proletariat being happy with their place.

I have been a student at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Many students, including me, find it hard to get around campus. My freshman year, I lived in East Halls, the farthest dorm from the center of campus. Walking to classes, like in the Willard building, could take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather. In the past, East Halls was far from the rest of the school. Now, new sports fields and buildings, like the new Creamery and health services, have been built there. As campus grows, it becomes harder to move around. What's the best solution? Bicycles are helpful, but they won't work alone. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be friendly for bicycles.

I talked to a friend who started riding his bike again after a long break. He said, "Bikes are great. They are the best way to get around." Bicycling is good for your body and fast. You can travel far with just oatmeal and a bit of effort. I now live off campus, far from the center. This year, I bought a bike. Class in Thomas building, 25 minutes walk from my house, takes only 5 minutes by bike. Pollock Road is the fastest way to get there by bike, but it's not always easy. Walking is an option, but I am too busy. Without my bike, walking would be my only choice. Walking to Thomas every day would take 30-40 minutes. That's more than two and a half hours a week. Adding time for other classes and appointments, it's too much time.
